{"cursor":"4215","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n.]] The 'Scholarly method' or 'scholarship' is the body of principles and\npractices used by to make their claims about the world as valid and trustworthy\nas possible, and to make them known to the scholarly public. It is the methods\nthat systemically advance the teaching, research, and practice of a given\nscholarly or academic field of study through rigorous inquiry. Scholarship is\nnoted by its significance to its particular profession, is creative, can be\ndocumented, can be replicated or elaborated, and can be and is peer-reviewed\nthrough various methods. http://www.aacn.nche.edu/publications/position/defining-\nscholarship Retrieved 15OCT2012.\n","linknr":152,"url":"Scholar","recorded":1362666500,"links":15,"instances":["mathematics","social_theory","publishing"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Academia","Scholars","Methodology","Critical thinking"],"headings":["Methods","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c6/Gerbrand_van_den_Eeckhout_003.jpg/260px-Gerbrand_van_den_Eeckhout_003.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Wikiquote-logo-en.svg/40px-Wikiquote-logo-en.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["practice","social_theory"],["variable","mathematics"],["open_access","publishing"]],"members":["variable","practice","open_access"],"related":["Principle","Practice_(social_theory)","Philosophy","Classical_philosophy","Scholasticism","Dialectical_reasoning","Historical_method","Historian","Primary_source","Historiography","Philosophy_of_history","Epistemology","E